<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="85" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
Epigyne of this species is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. chagyabensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="chagyabensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">A. chagyabensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hu &amp; Li, 1987, a species known from Xizang Autonomous Region of China. Both species are lacking anterior hood, have base of septum width much longer than septal stem length, both have distinct copulatory opening, but can be separated by septum width/length ratio 2.5 in 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. disca" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="disca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">A. disca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 1.8 in 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. chagyabensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="chagyabensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">A. chagyabensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Two species well differ by the shape of the endogyne (compare Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Alopecosa disca Peng, Yin, Zhang &amp; Kim, 1997, female. A Habitus, dorsal view B eyes, front view C chelicera, ventral view D sternum, ventral view E epigyne F vulva G vulva, showing the detailed left half H vulva, moved slightly from the normal ventral view I vulva, showing the detailed right half. Abbreviations: Ag accessorial gland, Cd copulatory duct, Sb septal base, Sp spermatheca, Ss septal stalk. Scale bars: 1 mm (A, B, D); 0.5 mm (C); 0.1 mm (E-I)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.945.52287.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/428129" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">1F-I</figureCitation>
and fig. 64-2 in 
<bibRefCitation author="Hu, JL" journalOrPublisher="Henan Science and Technology Publishing House, Zhengzhou" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" refId="B2" refString="Hu, JL, 2001. Spiders in Qinghai-Tibet Plateau of China. Henan Science and Technology Publishing House, Zhengzhou" title="Spiders in Qinghai-Tibet Plateau of China." year="2001">Hu 2001</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
